VALUES
(43, 6, 33, 62, 1, 1, 2, NULL, 'Connection of Life and Bread', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of life being given through divine means. John 6:33 speaks of the ''bread of God'' that gives life, while 1 John 1:1-2 refers to ''the Word of life'' that was manifested, highlighting the connection between divine provision and eternal life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 33, 54, 1, 15, 15, 'giveth life unto the world', 'Connection of Life and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the theme of Jesus as the source of life and salvation. Both passages emphasize that Jesus came into the world to provide life and save sinners.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 34, 43, 4, 15, 15, NULL, 'Desire for Spiritual Sustenance', 'Both passages emphasize a longing for sustenance that quenches spiritual thirst. The requests for ''this bread'' and ''this water'' illustrate a desire for deeper fulfillment beyond physical needs.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 34, 43, 6, 26, 26, 'this bread', 'Desire for Sustenance', 'Both passages emphasize the people''s desire for bread. In John 6:34, they ask for ''this bread,'' while in John 6:26, Jesus notes they sought him for the loaves they ate.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 34, 19, 4, 6, 6, 'Lord, evermore give us this bread', 'Desire for Divine Provision', 'This connection highlights a longing for sustenance and goodness. Both passages emphasize a plea for divine favor and the fulfillment of needs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 43, 6, 48, 58, 'I am the bread of life', 'Connection of Bread of Life', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the bread of life, highlighting the promise of eternal sustenance. The first passage introduces the concept, while the second elaborates on the necessity of consuming His flesh for eternal life.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 43, 6, 41, 41, 'I am the bread of life', 'Connection of Bread Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus as the ''bread'' that sustains life. The murmuring in John 6:41 reflects the challenge of accepting Jesus'' claim as the source of spiritual nourishment.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 66, 22, 17, 17, 'he that believeth on me shall never thirst', 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of spiritual sustenance, with Jesus identifying himself as the source of life and the invitation in Revelation extending to those who are thirsty. This connection highlights the offer of eternal satisfaction through belief and acceptance.', 'theme', 0.5309999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 23, 55, 1, 3, 'he that cometh to me shall never hunger', 'Connection of Spiritual Nourishment', 'Both passages emphasize the invitation to seek fulfillment through divine sustenance. Jesus identifies himself as the ''bread of life,'' paralleling Isaiah''s call to ''come ye to the waters'' for spiritual nourishment.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 23, 49, 10, 10, 'shall never hunger; and he that believeth on me shall never thirst', 'Connection of Hunger and Thirst', 'Both passages emphasize the assurance of not experiencing hunger or thirst. Jesus identifies himself as the source of sustenance, while Isaiah speaks of divine guidance that prevents hunger and thirst.', 'theme', 0.489, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 66, 7, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Hunger and Thirst', 'Both passages emphasize the absence of hunger and thirst. John 6:35 presents Jesus as the source of life that satisfies, while Revelation 7:16 describes a future state where hunger and thirst no longer exist.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 35, 40, 11, 28, 28, NULL, 'Invitation to Find Rest', 'Both passages emphasize an invitation to come to Jesus for fulfillment and relief. John 6:35 speaks of never hungering or thirsting, while Matthew 11:28 offers rest to the weary.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 60, 1, 8, 9, 'believe not', 'Faith and Belief in Christ', 'This connection highlights the contrast between seeing and believing. John 6:36 notes the lack of belief despite seeing, while 1 Peter 1:8 emphasizes love and joy in believing without seeing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 42, 16, 31, 31, 'believe not', 'Unbelief Despite Evidence', 'This connection highlights the theme of disbelief in the face of clear evidence. Both passages emphasize that even when confronted with significant signs, such as seeing Jesus or a resurrection, some will still not believe.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 43, 6, 26, 26, 'believe not', 'Connection of Belief and Seeking', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of belief and the motivations behind seeking Jesus. In John 6:26, the crowd seeks Jesus not for spiritual reasons but for physical satisfaction, which is echoed in John 6:36 where their lack of belief is highlighted.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 43, 12, 37, 37, 'believe not', 'Unbelief Despite Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of unbelief despite witnessing Jesus'' presence and miracles. The repeated mention of not believing highlights a consistent response to Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 43, 6, 64, 64, 'believe not', 'Connection of Unbelief in John', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of unbelief among those who have seen Jesus. The mention of those who ''believe not'' in both verses highlights the recognition of disbelief in the presence of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 36, 43, 15, 24, 24, 'have seen me', 'Rejection of Jesus and His Works', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of seeing yet not believing. In John 6:36, the rejection of Jesus is highlighted, while John 15:24 connects this rejection to the works He performed, indicating a deeper culpability in their disbelief.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 40, 11, 28, 28, 'come to me', 'Invitation to Come', 'Both passages emphasize an invitation to come to Jesus. John 6:37 mentions those given by the Father will come, while Matthew 11:28 invites all who labor to come for rest.', 'theme', 0.51, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 43, 6, 39, 39, NULL, 'Divine Assurance of Preservation', 'Both passages emphasize the assurance that those given by the Father to the Son will not be lost. The phrase ''all which he hath given me'' in John 6:39 directly connects to the promise of acceptance in John 6:37.', 'theme', 0.475, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 43, 17, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Divine Giving', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of those given by the Father to the Son. In John 6:37, it states that those given will come to Jesus, while John 17:24 refers to those given being with Him to behold His glory.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 23, 55, 7, 7, 'him that cometh to me', 'Invitation to Return and Mercy', 'Both passages emphasize the invitation to come to God and the assurance of mercy for those who do. John 6:37 speaks of those who come to Jesus not being cast out, while Isaiah 55:7 encourages the wicked to return to the Lord for abundant pardon.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 55, 2, 19, 19, 'him that cometh to me', 'Divine Assurance of Belonging', 'This connection highlights the assurance of belonging to God. Both passages emphasize that those who come to Christ are known and accepted by Him, reinforcing the idea of divine recognition and commitment.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 58, 4, 15, 15, 'him that cometh to me', 'Connection of Compassion and Acceptance', 'This connection highlights the theme of acceptance in both passages. John 6:37 emphasizes that those who come to Jesus will not be cast out, while Hebrews 4:15 illustrates Jesus'' empathy towards human weaknesses.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 37, 23, 1, 18, 19, 'him that cometh to me', 'Invitation to Come', 'Both passages emphasize the invitation to come to God. John 6:37''s assurance of acceptance parallels Isaiah 1:18''s call to reason together, highlighting God''s willingness to receive those who approach Him.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 43, 5, 30, 30, 'not to do mine own will', 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of seeking the will of the Father rather than one''s own will. This connection highlights Jesus'' submission to divine authority in His mission.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 43, 4, 34, 34, 'the will of him that sent me', 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize doing the will of him that sent Jesus. This connection highlights the importance of obedience to God''s purpose in Jesus'' mission.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 50, 2, 7, 8, 'to do mine own will', 'Connection of Obedience and Humility', 'Both passages emphasize obedience to God''s will. John 6:38 highlights Jesus'' commitment to doing the will of God, while Philippians 2:7-8 illustrates His humility and obedience, culminating in His death.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 19, 40, 7, 8, 'to do mine own will', 'Connection of Divine Will', 'Both passages emphasize the commitment to doing God''s will. John 6:38 reflects Jesus'' mission to fulfill the will of God, while Psalms 40:7-8 expresses a delight in doing God''s will, indicating a shared theme of obedience and purpose.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 6, 38, 23, 53, 10, 10, 'not to do mine own will', 'Divine Will and Suffering', 'This connection highlights the theme of fulfilling divine will through suffering. Both passages emphasize the obedience to God''s purpose, with John 6:38 reflecting Jesus'' submission to the will of God and Isaiah 53:10 indicating that it pleased the Lord to bruise him as part of that divine plan.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
